Your FinOps Question: S3 vs. ECR Endpoints
You asked: "If we are fixing S3 to bypass the NAT Gateway, should we also fix ECR?"

This is a Senior-level FinOps interview question. The answer is: No, leaving ECR on the NAT Gateway is actually the best practice for your current architecture. Here is the math why:

There are two types of VPC Endpoints in AWS:

Gateway Endpoints (For S3 and DynamoDB): These are 100% FREE. There is zero reason not to use them. It routes all your WordPress image uploads for free. We will build this.

Interface Endpoints / PrivateLink (For ECR, ECS, Secrets Manager): These cost an hourly fee just to exist (about $7 to $15 per month).

The FinOps Calculation: Your NAT Gateway charges you $0.045 per Gigabyte of data processed.
Your Docker image is about 500MB. If you deploy code 4 times a day, that is 2GB of data, which costs you $0.09 per day through the NAT Gateway (about $2.70 a month).
If we built an ECR Interface Endpoint to bypass the NAT, you would pay $15 a month for the endpoint!

By leaving ECR on the NAT Gateway and putting S3 on a free Gateway Endpoint, you are executing the absolute cheapest, most highly optimized FinOps strategy possible. (Keep this explanation in your back pocket for your interviews!)

The Phase 7 Roadmap
Here is the exact plan for Phase 7. We will write a few new Terraform files to lock down your production environment.

1. The FinOps Lock-down (Cost Control)
The S3 Gateway Endpoint: We will write the Terraform block to build the free tunnel for your WordPress media files.

Log Retention Limits: Right now, your CloudWatch logs are set to "Keep Forever." In 5 years, you will be paying hundreds of dollars for dead logs. We will set a strict 30-day deletion policy.

AWS Budgets: We will create a billing alarm so if your AWS account accidentally goes over $20, you get an email instantly.

2. The Security Lock-down (AWS WAF)
Right now, anyone in the world can run a script to guess WordPress passwords on your login screen 10,000 times a second.

We will attach an AWS WAFv2 (Web Application Firewall) to your CloudFront distribution. We will configure a rule to automatically block any IP address that hits your login page more than 100 times in 5 minutes.

3. Observability (The "Mission Control" Dashboard)
CloudWatch Container Insights: We will turn on X-Ray vision for ECS so you can see exactly how much CPU and Memory client3 is using versus client4.

Tripwire Alarms: We will write code using aws_cloudwatch_metric_alarm. If client3's Fargate container hits 85% CPU, or if the database crashes, it will trigger an AWS SNS topic that immediately sends a high-priority alert to your email address.